FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE, OVINE - CYPRUS (02): NOT
**********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

[1]
Date: Wed 31 Oct 2007
Source: The Associated Press [edited]
<http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/10/31/europe/EU-GEN-Cyprus-Livestock-Cordon.php>


A herd of sheep in Cyprus is not infected with foot and mouth disease
[FMD], agriculture minister Fotis Fotiou said, citing test results released
on Wednesday [31 Oct 2007] from a European Union laboratory in England.
"The tests do not confirm FMD; there is nothing for us to be concerned
about," Fotiou told the AP.

Last week, authorities cordoned off an area in south east Cyprus,
suspecting infection in a herd of 320 sheep in village of Dromolaxia.

Wednesday's [31 Oct 2007] results were greeted by relief from local
farmers, as 150 000 farm animals, including cows and pigs on dozens of
farms, would likely have been culled within a 10 km (6 mile) radius of an
infected herd.

Fotiou said the cull would have been a financial "disaster" for this tiny
island's farmers. The Cypriot samples were tested at the EU laboratory in
Weybridge [sic; should read Pirbright], England.

--
