ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[2]
Date: Wed 31 Oct 2007
Source: Reuters [edited]
<http://www.reuters.com/article/healthNews/idUSWRI13372920071031>


Cyprus on Wednesday [31 Oct 2007] said initial tests had failed to verify a
suspected outbreak of foot and mouth disease [FMD] at a farm on the island.
Authorities have quarantined a farm in the south of the island after sheep
showed symptoms of the debilitating and highly contagious disease last week.

"The 1st indications we have from the laboratory is that it does not appear
to be FMD, but that does not mean it is the conclusive result," agriculture
minister Photis Photiou said.

Conclusive results were expected from Britain on Wednesday [31 Oct 2007]
afternoon, he said [and received by now: negative; see item 1 above. - Mod.AS].

Farmers say the sheep affected probably fell ill by consuming sumac, a
shrub which grows in the wild [see 3].

